   =20
      Shadow ETF trading
   =20
 =20

A lot of readers of this column are clever, financially literate, and =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0let=E2=80=99s say ethically flexible, or at least, easily able =
to imagine hypothetical ethical flexibility? I don=E2=80=99t know. The poin=
t is that people are always coming to me with ideas for how to get away wit=
h insider trading. NOTHING IN THIS COLUMN IS EVER LEGAL ADVICE, PARTICULARL=
Y NOT WHEN WE TALK ABOUT CLEVER WAYS TO DO CRIMES, but here we are. The   m=
ost common and =E2=80=A6=C2=A0best??? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0suggestion goes like t=
his:
=09You work at, or with,=C2=A0a public company, and you learn some big secr=
et news about the company. It=E2=80=99s getting acquired at a premium, it h=
as very good or very bad earnings coming, it got hacked, it found a cure fo=
r cancer, whatever. Something that will predictably make the stock go up or=
 down a lot.=09You do=C2=A0not=C2=A0go out and buy (or sell) your company=
=E2=80=99s stock! You will get caught!=09Nor do you go out and buy short-da=
ted options on the stock; that=E2=80=99s even worse.=09Nor do you tell your=
 college buddy or brother-in-law the news, so that=C2=A0he=C2=A0can buy opt=
ions and make money and give you a paper bag full of cash as a payoff for t=
he tip. One, that is obviously illegal, and two, it tends to get caught. Re=
gulators notice suspicious trades ahead of big corporate news, and they inv=
estigate them, and they are able to figure out that this guy is your colleg=
e buddy or brother-in-law and connect his trading to you.=09Instead, you=C2=
=A0trade something else. You buy (or sell) something else that is=C2=A0corr=
elated=C2=A0to your company=E2=80=99s stock, so that when your company anno=
unces its news, that other thing will predictably go up (or down) and you c=
an make money without ever trading your own company=E2=80=99s securities.=
=09(Or you tip your buddy or brother-in-law, but make sure that he only tra=
des the correlated asset, not your stock.)=09The idea =E2=80=94=C2=A0which =
I cannot endorse! =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that, when a company announces big news=
, regulators look for suspicious trading in=C2=A0that company=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0stock, but they don=E2=80=99t look for suspicious trading in correlated =
things, so they won=E2=80=99t catch you.=09The other idea =E2=80=94=C2=A0wh=
ich I also cannot endorse! =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that you are not an insider of=
 the correlated thing, so it=E2=80=99s not insider trading. Even if the reg=
ulators do notice, they can=E2=80=99t do anything about it, because it is n=
ot illegal. (Again: This is a theory, but not my theory, and certainly not =
the regulators=E2=80=99 theory.)=09One obvious way to do this is to buy (or=
 sell) the stock of some competitor company, or a couple of competitors: Go=
od earnings for your company might predict good earnings for its whole indu=
stry, etc. (This is not always easy =E2=80=94=C2=A0if your company has been=
 hacked, does that mean your competitors are vulnerable and should go down,=
 or that they=E2=80=99ll win market share and should go up? If your company=
 is getting acquired, does that mean that your competitors are also in play=
, or that the only potential acquirer has made its choice and they aren=E2=
=80=99t it? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but probably=C2=A0sometimes=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s ea=
sy.)=09Another obvious way to do this is to buy (or sell) a=C2=A0sector exc=
hange-traded fund=C2=A0containing all the stocks in your industry. That mig=
ht be neater and easier than picking a couple of competitors to buy, and it=
 has the possible advantage that the ETF includes=C2=A0your own company=E2=
=80=99s stock and so benefits more directly from your company=E2=80=99s new=
s. And yet it arguably looks less suspicious: You can say =E2=80=9CI would =
never trade in my own company=E2=80=99s stock, to avoid even a hint of impr=
opriety, but I am bullish on our industry as a whole so I bought some of ou=
r sector ETF.=E2=80=9D

These approaches =E2=80=94=C2=A0points 9 and 10 above, using inside informa=
tion about one company to make informed trades in correlated stocks or ETFs
  [3]
=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0are sometimes called =E2=80=9Cshadow trading.=E2=80=9D
One question that you might have is: Is shadow trading=C2=A0illegal?=C2=A0I=
s it insider trading? Is point 8 wrong?=C2=A0I am not going to give you leg=
al advice, but it seems clear that the US Securities and Exchange Commissio=
n thinks that shadow trading is illegal =E2=80=94=C2=A0it   brought a case =
against an alleged shadow trader in 2021 =E2=80=94=C2=A0and my view is that=
 they are correct. I like to say that insider trading, in the US, is not ab=
out=C2=A0fairness=C2=A0but about=C2=A0theft, and using your company=E2=80=
=99s secret information to make money trading some other stock is probably =
theft-y enough to count. (There are ambiguities, though. If your  company=
=E2=80=99s insider trading policy says things like =E2=80=9Cyou cannot use =
secret information you learn on the job to trade=C2=A0anything,=E2=80=9D th=
en your shadow trading is probably illegal, but if your policy says =E2=80=
=9Cyou can=E2=80=99t use secret information you learn on the job to trade=
=C2=A0our company=E2=80=99s stock,=E2=80=9D then maybe you=E2=80=99re okay?=
)
Another question that you might have is: Do the regulators look for this? I=
f you trade in correlated things, will the SEC come after you? Is point 7 w=
rong? I don=E2=80=99t know, and if I did I wouldn=E2=80=99t tell you, becau=
se I am certainly not in the business of telling you how to get away with c=
rimes.
But another question you might have is: Does shadow trading=C2=A0happen a l=
ot?=C2=A0Are there a ton of corporate insiders and deal advisers who are re=
gularly making shadow trades in order to profit from inside information? So=
me casual empirical data:
=09
Very=C2=A0few people get=C2=A0caught=C2=A0shadow trading; I can only really=
 think of the one enforcement action. This could mean that it is very rare,=
 or conversely it could mean that it happens all the time but the SEC is no=
t in fact looking for it.=C2=A0=09Readers do keep suggesting it to me! I do=
n=E2=80=99t know what that tells you.

But this is also of academic interest and so sometimes you get more formal =
empirical data. We have  talked about a  paper by Mihir Mehta, David Reeb a=
nd Wanli Zhao, which seems to have coined the term =E2=80=9Cshadow trading,=
=E2=80=9D and which found =E2=80=9Cincreased levels of informed trading amo=
ng business partners and competitors before a firm releases private informa=
tion=E2=80=9D: People with inside information about one company=C2=A0do=C2=
=A0seem to be trading correlated companies.=C2=A0
And here is a new paper on =E2=80=9CUsing ETFs to Conceal Insider Trading,=
=E2=80=9D by=C2=A0Elza Egl=C4=ABte,=C2=A0Dans =C5=A0taermans,=C2=A0Vinay Pa=
tel and=C2=A0T=C4=81lis Putni=C5=86=C5=A1:
We show that exchange traded funds (ETFs) are used in a new form of insider=
 trading known as =E2=80=9Cshadow trading.=E2=80=9D Our evidence suggests t=
hat some traders in possession of material non-public information about upc=
oming M&A announcements trade in ETFs that contain the target stock, rather=
 than trading the underlying company shares, thereby concealing their insid=
er trading. Using bootstrap techniques to identify abnormal trading in trea=
tment and control samples, we find significant levels of shadow trading in =
3-6% of same-industry ETFs prior to M&A announcements, equating to at least=
 $212 million of such trading per annum. Our findings suggest insider tradi=
ng is more pervasive than just the =E2=80=9Cdirect=E2=80=9D forms that have=
 been the focus of research and enforcement to date.
They point out that ETFs have some advantages for shadow trading:
ETFs provide an attractive instrument for insiders to trade their private i=
nformation for several reasons. First, the stock that is the subject of the=
 information may be a constituent of the ETF, so that one can get a direct =
exposure to the company=E2=80=99s share price via the ETF, but in a vehicle=
 that is more subtle than trading the company shares directly, helping redu=
ce scrutiny from law enforcement. Second, ETFs are cost-effective and often=
 more liquid than the underlying company shares (e.g., Buckle et al., 2018)=
, potentially reducing the price impact of insider trades. Both theoretical=
 and empirical evidence shows that insiders trade in highly liquid assets s=
o that they can hide their information and maximize their trading profits (=
e.g., Lei and Wang, 2014; Ben-David et al., 2018). Third, shadow trading in=
 ETFs prior to price-sensitive news allows insiders to benefit from increas=
es in the price of both the source firm and related firms.
I look forward to reading the SEC=E2=80=99s first ETF shadow trading enforc=
ement action, though I worry that the complaint will have a paragraph like =
=E2=80=9Cbefore buying these short-dated call options on the sector ETF, th=
e defendant spent an hour reading Money Stuff for advice on shadow trading.=
=E2=80=9D Don=E2=80=99t do that!

