10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">WhatsApp</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is not literally the case that the US Secur=
ities and Exchange Commission is a for-profit business whose goal is to max=
imize its revenue, and whose most important source of revenue is fining fin=
ancial services companies for their misdeeds.<a class=3D"footnote-index" hr=
ef=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: in=
line-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But that is sometimes a tempting way to think about things. If yo=
u are an entrepreneurial SEC enforcement attorney sitting in your office th=
inking of things to enforce, you might prefer to enforce things that are ea=
sy to turn into large amounts of=C2=A0money. If a bankrupt company did an i=
diosyncratic bad thing, that=E2=80=99s bad, but how much money are you goin=
g to extract from one bankrupt company? If every single mega-bank did the s=
ame questionable thing, that is much more promising, on a strictly monetary=
=C2=A0basis.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/30437332.271447/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMjgvdGhlLWRlbGktd2FzLWFsbGVnZWRseS1hLWZyYXVkP2N=
tcGlkPUJCRDAyMDIyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZX=
dzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIwMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cBddd00a93" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked before</a> about the SEC=E2=80=99=
s probe into how the employees of big banks discussed their work in text me=
ssages and chat apps like WhatsApp on their personal cell phones. The SEC h=
as collected big fines from the biggest banks because, it has said, these c=
hats violated the SEC=E2=80=99s recordkeeping requirements. When the SEC fi=
ned 15 banks and brokers for this stuff in September, <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30437332.271447/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmd=
vdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi0xNzQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5507a4c4"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> SEC Chair Gary Gensler said</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Since the 1930s, such recordkeepin=
g has been vital to preserve market integrity. As technology changes, it=E2=
=80=99s even more important that registrants appropriately conduct their co=
mmunications about business matters within only official channels, and they=
 must maintain and preserve those communications.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From the perspective of the=C2=A0<em>banks</em=
>, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30437332.271447=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMjgvdG=
hlLWRlbGktd2FzLWFsbGVnZWRseS1hLWZyYXVkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMDIyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJ=
nV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIwMiZ1=
dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCddd00a93" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  I have argued</a>, this is a novel expansion of the SEC=E2=80=99s authori=
ty. When the SEC created its rules on recordkeeping, it required banks to r=
etain copies of their =E2=80=9Cinter-office memoranda,=E2=80=9D but it was =
1948 and those memoranda were produced with carbon paper; they were formal =
business records memorializing serious policies. In the 2020s, WhatsApp cha=
ts are, in large part,=C2=A0substitutes not for=C2=A0<em>formal memoranda=
=C2=A0</em>but for <em>talking to someone in person</em>. When I was a bank=
er, I have written,=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThere were some mornings when I sent more=
 than 100 inter-office memoranda, though like 20 of them would be =E2=80=98=
lol=E2=80=99 or =E2=80=98fml.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D In 1948, the SEC would not =
have dreamed of demanding a searchable archive of all of the informal chats=
 held at a brokerage: That was not technologically feasible, and also did n=
ot seem to be the point of its rules. In 2022, it was feasible, and the SEC=
 did demand it, and when the brokers were missing some chats they paid a bi=
llion dollars in fines.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From the perspective of the <em>SEC</em>, as a=
 fine-maximizing business, this series of investigations is=C2=A0<em>so </e=
m>attractive:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Every bank has some bankers who did W=
hatsApp chats, so you can fine all of them, and they all have a lot of mone=
y and depend on the SEC=E2=80=99s goodwill, so they=E2=80=99ll pay.</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You don=E2=80=99t have to prove bad <em>i=
ntent</em>, or <em>harm: </em>Simply finding some WhatsApp chats about deal=
s, or clients, or market conditions, or anything, is enough to extract a bi=
g fine. If the SEC had gotten the personal messages of a bunch of bankers a=
nd found them doing a bunch of crimes, it surely would have extracted more =
fines from them, but as far as I can tell it never found anything like that=
. The bankers had normal businesslike chats about client meetings or market=
s or whatever, but the fact that they were on WhatsApp was enough to incur =
a billion dollars of liability.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Ba=
nks will learn their lesson from these enforcement actions, and the lesson =
is =E2=80=9Ckeep all communications on official channels and preserve all o=
f them,=E2=80=9D which will make it easier for the SEC to catch=C2=A0<em>fu=
ture </em>misbehavior and fine it comprehensively.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If I worked at a bank I=E2=80=99d be very anno=
yed by the WhatsApp stuff, but as it is I sort of admire it: It is, for the=
 SEC, a clever bit of business, a bold expansion into a lucrative and growi=
ng market, and an investment in making its future business easier.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC clearly agrees, because=C2=A0its Whats=
App Fines Division keeps <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/30437332.271447/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVz=
LzIwMjMtMDItMDIvd2hhdHNhcHAtcHJvYmUtaGl0cy1iaWctaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtYXMtc2VjLWF=
za3MtZm9yLXBob25lLXJldmlldz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjAyMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaX=
VtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAyMDImdXRtX2NhbXBha=
WduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd53c1f9f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  moving into=
 new markets</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Major hedge funds have been asked by US regula=
tors to review certain employees=E2=80=99 personal mobile phones as part of=
 a mushrooming probe into Wall Street=E2=80=99s use of unofficial messaging=
 platforms like WhatsApp to conduct business.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission recentl=
y asked Steve Cohen=E2=80=99s Point72 Asset Management, Ken Griffin=E2=80=
=99s Citadel and several other firms to search through the devices for evid=
ence of business dealings on unapproved channels, according to people famil=
iar with the matter who asked not to be identified discussing the private r=
equests. The SEC is also probing the practices of brokerages, money manager=
s and private equity firms.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Representatives for Point72 and Citadel declin=
ed to comment. Neither firm has been accused of wrongdoing. The inquiries a=
re part of a broader request that also went to other hedge funds, the peopl=
e said. The SEC declined to comment.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The asset-management industry is quickly emerg=
ing as the new front in the SEC=E2=80=99s sweeping look into whether financ=
ial professionals are using unofficial communications to do things like cut=
 deals, win clients or make trades. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Although the SEC had previously asked investme=
nt firms for information on policies and key staff whose texts and emails a=
re supposed to be archived, a request to image and review the devices has s=
parked fresh pushback. On Tuesday, top industry trade groups sent Gensler a=
 letter, citing =E2=80=9Cserious privacy implications.=E2=80=9D ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The trade groups argued that the SEC was overr=
eaching in its request. The regulator, they said, was seeking to improperly=
 hold investment advisers to a standard that=E2=80=99s meant for brokerages=
 and not money managers.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The appeal of this investigation is that at ev=
ery big company there will be people who have texted about business on thei=
r personal cell phones, and the right model is to go down the list and hit =
all the biggest financial businesses up for fines.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It really is wild that the SEC=E2=80=99s offic=
ial position is now that it is illegal to =E2=80=9Cuse unofficial communica=
tions to do things like cut deals, win clients or make trades.=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=9CConduct their communications about business matters within only offic=
ial channels=E2=80=9D! Imagine if that was really the rule! You can=E2=80=
=99t have lunch with a client and talk about business, or have beers with y=
our colleagues and gripe about work, because that does not create a searcha=
ble archive for the SEC to review.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course the SEC does not entirely mean this.=
 Yet. But in like five years, technology =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the SEC=E2=80=
=99s interpretation of the rules =E2=80=94 will have advanced to the point =
that banks will get fined if their bankers talk about business with clients=
 on the golf course. =E2=80=9CYou should have been wearing your bank-issued=
 virtual reality headset and recorded the conversation,=E2=80=9D the SEC wi=
ll say, or I guess =E2=80=9Cyou should have played golf in your bank=E2=80=
=99s official metaverse, which records all golf conversations for complianc=
e review,=C2=A0rather than on a physical golf course.=E2=80=9D The golf cou=
rse is an unofficial channel! No business allowed!</p>
