<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Shadow ETF trading</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A lot of readers of this column are clever, fi=
nancially literate, and =E2=80=A6=C2=A0let=E2=80=99s say ethically flexible=
, or at least, easily able to imagine hypothetical ethical flexibility? I d=
on=E2=80=99t know. The point is that people are always coming to me with id=
eas for how to get away with insider trading. NOTHING IN THIS COLUMN IS EVE=
R LEGAL ADVICE, PARTICULARLY NOT WHEN WE TALK ABOUT CLEVER WAYS TO DO CRIME=
S, but here we are. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/30437332.271447/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjAtMDctMTYvYS12YWNjaW5lLWNvdWxkLWN1cmUtYWlybGluZXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIw=
MjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXR=
tX3Rlcm09MjMwMjAyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
ecc8b785" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">  most common</a> and =E2=80=A6=C2=A0best??? =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0suggestion goes like this:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You work at, or with,=C2=A0a public c=
ompany, and you learn some big secret news about the company. It=E2=80=99s =
getting acquired at a premium, it has very good or very bad earnings coming=
, it got hacked, it found a cure for cancer, whatever. Something that will =
predictably make the stock go up or down a lot.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">You do=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>go out and buy (or sell) your c=
ompany=E2=80=99s stock! You will get caught!</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 5px;">Nor do you go out and buy short-dated options on the stock; that=
=E2=80=99s even worse.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Nor do you =
tell your college buddy or brother-in-law the news, so that=C2=A0<em>he=C2=
=A0</em>can buy options and make money and give you a paper bag full of cas=
h as a payoff for the tip. One, that is obviously illegal, and two, it tend=
s to get caught. Regulators notice suspicious trades ahead of big corporate=
 news, and they investigate them, and they are able to figure out that this=
 guy is your college buddy or brother-in-law and connect his trading to you=
.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Instead, you=C2=A0<em>trade some=
thing else</em>. You buy (or sell) something else that is=C2=A0<em>correlat=
ed=C2=A0</em>to your company=E2=80=99s stock, so that when your company ann=
ounces its news, that other thing will predictably go up (or down) and you =
can make money without ever trading your own company=E2=80=99s securities.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">(Or you tip your buddy or brother-=
in-law, but make sure that he only trades the correlated asset, not your st=
ock.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The idea =E2=80=94=C2=A0whic=
h I cannot endorse! =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that, when a company announces big ne=
ws, regulators look for suspicious trading in=C2=A0<em>that company=E2=80=
=99s=C2=A0</em>stock, but they don=E2=80=99t look for suspicious trading in=
 correlated things, so they won=E2=80=99t catch you.</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">The other idea =E2=80=94=C2=A0which I also cannot endors=
e! =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that you are not an insider of the correlated thing, s=
o it=E2=80=99s not insider trading. Even if the regulators do notice, they =
can=E2=80=99t do anything about it, because it is not illegal. (Again: This=
 is a theory, but not my theory, and certainly not the regulators=E2=80=99 =
theory.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">One obvious way to do thi=
s is to buy (or sell) the stock of some competitor company, or a couple of =
competitors: Good earnings for your company might predict good earnings for=
 its whole industry, etc. (This is not always easy =E2=80=94=C2=A0if your c=
ompany has been hacked, does that mean your competitors are vulnerable and =
should go down, or that they=E2=80=99ll win market share and should go up? =
If your company is getting acquired, does that mean that your competitors a=
re also in play, or that the only potential acquirer has made its choice an=
d they aren=E2=80=99t it? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but probably=C2=A0<em>sometimes=C2=
=A0</em>it=E2=80=99s easy.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Anothe=
r obvious way to do this is to buy (or sell) a=C2=A0<em>sector exchange-tra=
ded fund=C2=A0</em>containing all the stocks in your industry. That might b=
e neater and easier than picking a couple of competitors to buy, and it has=
 the possible advantage that the ETF <em>includes=C2=A0</em>your own compan=
y=E2=80=99s stock and so benefits more directly from your company=E2=80=99s=
 news. And yet it arguably looks less suspicious: You can say =E2=80=9CI wo=
uld never trade in my own company=E2=80=99s stock, to avoid even a hint of =
impropriety, but I am bullish on our industry as a whole so I bought some o=
f our sector ETF.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These approaches =E2=80=94=C2=A0points 9 and 1=
0 above, using inside information about one company to make informed trades=
 in correlated stocks or ETFs<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-=
3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impor=
tant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0are sometimes called =E2=80=9Cshadow trading.=E2=
=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One question that you might have is: Is shadow=
 trading=C2=A0<em>illegal?=C2=A0</em>Is it insider trading? Is point 8 wron=
g?=C2=A0I am not going to give you legal advice, but it seems clear that th=
e US Securities and Exchange Commission thinks that shadow trading is illeg=
al =E2=80=94=C2=A0it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/30437332.271447/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVz=
LzIwMjEtMDgtMjMvc3BhYy1zdWl0LWxlYWRzLXRvLXNwYXJjcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjAyMjNfTU9=
ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT=
0yMzAyMDImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0ef26264=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">  brought a case against an alleged shadow trader</a> in 2021 =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and my view is that they are correct. I like to say that inside=
r trading, in the US, is not about=C2=A0<em>fairness=C2=A0</em>but about=C2=
=A0<em>theft</em>, and using your company=E2=80=99s secret information to m=
ake money trading some other stock is probably theft-y enough to count. (Th=
ere are ambiguities, though. If your <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/30437332.271447/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdz=
